Picture: Annika Enderborg Manly Fight for the Liberal candidate to replace Mike Baird in Manly has been narrowed down to three Robbie Patterson, Manly Daily February 21, 2017 5:18pm Greens strike first in battle for Manly Would-be pollies in fight for Mike Baird’s vacant seat Activists threaten to turn Manly into Orange by-election
THE next Liberal candidate for Manly will be chosen by local members after the party’s head office vote of 56 delegates failed to ­determine a clear winner.
The race to replace former premier and outgoing Manly MP Mike Baird has been narrowed down to three top candidates after an initial vote, according to sources.
media_camera Liberal party conservative favourite Walter Villatora poses during a photo shoot at the beach near his Manly home. Picture: Troy Snook.
The votes — made up of 20 members of the Liberal Party’s state executive and 36 people drawn from electorates across the state — gave a majority to former Manly councillor James Griffin.
But conservative favourite, leader of the democratic reform movement Walter Villatora, and chief executive of Restaurant and Catering Australia John Hart, were also well ­represented.
The candidate will be ­announced in the next ­fortnight with the winner needing 71 votes.
media_camera Former Manly councillor James Griffin.
A total of 84 locals from the Manly electorate will vote in the preselection.
It follows the shock exit of Young Liberals NSW president Alex Dore before a ­single vote was counted. It is understood Mr Dore quit the race to give Mr Villatora a better shot at winning.
A source said he quit in time to use his vote as part of the party’s state executive and feared that his involvement in the preselection would dilute the chances of other right wing candidates.
media_camera CEO of the Restaurant and Catering Association, John Hart. Picture: Jane Dempster.
“There was no real clear win for anyone from the central component (at head office),” a Liberal source said.
“No one is claiming it ­either. Now it is up to the ­locals to vote in their ­member , which is the way it should be .”

February 21st 2017 6 hours ago /video/video.news.com.au/News/World/ The Moment Kim Jong Nam Was Attacked: CCTV Footage It is understood ­Mr Griffin received the ­majority of votes from the state executive, but a source said it was not enough to claim victory.
Another source said that Rob Giltinan, a former under-18 tennis star turned model turned adviser to Premier Gladys Berejiklian, could still be in the mix.
